- The intimate in‑the‑room candidate, while very close to many of my tastes (analogue warmth, preserved transients, tight guitars, concise sequencing), explicitly emphasizes “close, forward lead vocals.” That vocal proximity is the deciding negative: my self‑introduction specifies a preference for natural, roomy lead vocals (not ultra‑close/glassy). A forward, in‑the‑room vocal presentation risks pushing into the ultra‑close territory that undermines the warm, ambient vocal character I prefer and can shift focus away from the rhythmic drive I prize.
- In short: both discs have many strengths, but Abbey Road aligns more closely with my primary priorities — preserved dynamics and transient detail plus a rhythm‑forward, punchy low‑compression mix — while the other candidate’s overtly close vocal presentation runs counter to my explicit dislike of ultra‑close/glassy lead vocals and could reduce the rhythmic immediacy I favor.

